  <section class="sec">
    <p class="sl">Local knowledge</p>
    <h2>Sunshine West — Postwar Inner West, 1940s–1960s Fibro & Brick, High Density of Original Fireplaces</h2>
    <div class="local-box"><p>Sunshine West is a densely settled inner-western suburb developed primarily through the 1940s and 1950s as the postwar housing boom expanded the industrial Sunshine precinct. The suburb's housing stock is characterised by fibro and weatherboard cottages and early brick veneer homes from that era — a very high proportion of which were fitted with open fireplaces as the standard form of heating. These original fireplace systems are still present in a large majority of Sunshine West homes and many remain in regular use, making the suburb one of the higher-demand areas for chimney cleaning in Melbourne's western corridor. The proximity to the Maribyrnong River creates a cold air drainage pattern in winter — cold air settles along the river valley and into the lower-lying streets of Sunshine West, and the suburb's inland position away from any coastal moderating effect means winter nights can be genuinely cold despite the inner-suburban location. June and July typically bring overnight temperatures between three and six degrees, and wood fires are common from May through August. We service Sunshine West as part of our inner-west Melbourne run and are familiar with the fibro-era and early brick homes, the fireplace configurations of that period, and the issues that arise with older chimneys that have been in continuous seasonal use for over sixty years.</p></div>
  </section>

